  "body_html": "<i>Diagram illustrating Lumbricals</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb039b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb039.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lumbricals'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb039b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><b>Key Knowledge Summary</b><br /><br /><b>Origin</b><br /><ul><li>Flexor digitorum profundus</li></ul><b>Insertion</b><br /><ul><li>Radial side of extensor expansion of corresponding finger</li></ul><b>Innervation</b><br /><ul><li>1st & 2nd lumbricals (the most radial two) are innervated by the <b>median nerve</b></li><li>3rd & 4th lumbricals (most ulnar two) are innervated by the <b>deep branch of the ulnar nerve</b></li></ul><b>Actions</b><br /><ul><li>Flex metacarpophalangeal joints</li><li>Extend interphalangeal joints</li></ul><br />Video explaining the anatomy of the lumbricals <br /><br /><iframe width='560' height='315' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/H</td><td>481JVpc5U?list=PL9VD5O7cGHAazuRnYR5MLdJQ7KHBBQtS0' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen></iframe><br /><br /></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">6</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Anatomy</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Upper limb anatomy</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<i>Diagram illustrating Lumbricals</i><br /><br /><CENTER><tab